(118, 0, 126, 2, 'on', 2, '2', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:46:"Economics/Politics: Keystone Pipeline Rejected";s:7:"content";s:8640:"<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\"><strong>Economics and Politics:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: medium;\\"><strong>Obama Rejects Keystone Pipeline Construction</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: x-small;\\">Written by Cheyenne Williams</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: x-small;\\"><img title=\\"Keystone Pipeline Map\\" src=\\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/rf/image_296w/2010-2019/WashingtonPost/2011/11/10/Web-Resampled/2011-11-10/w-PipelineMAP296--300x350.jpg\\" alt=\\"Keystone Pipeline Map\\" width=\\"173\\" height=\\"213\\" /><img title=\\"Keystone Pipeline Sit-In\\" src=\\"http://img3.allvoices.com/thumbs/image/609/480/87997532-keystone-pipeline.jpg\\" alt=\\"Keystone Pipeline Sit-In\\" width=\\"174\\" height=\\"209\\" /></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Around mid-January, the Obama Administration formally announced their rejection of the Keystone XL oil pipeline construction. The administration states that the congressional deadline for this decision set down during the previous pay-roll tax cut bill did not allow them enough time to consider all of the environmental issues impacting the project, despite that they were given sixty days in addition to the previous years spent over this pipeline. The pipeline builder having already spent much of its money in analyses and materials in anticipation of the project\\''s approval, David Goldwyn, a former State Department representative for international energy affairs who now heads a consulting firm, stated that the U.S. could reuse some of the studies and analyses it has already conducted, but the process would take \\"a minimum of 18 months to two years,\\" wasting much of the company\\''s time and money in the meantime.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">The tentativeness portrayed by this administration for the past few years over this Canadian pipeline deal brings to light in particular their political indecision over which two critical Democrat constituencies they ought to appease to in the upcoming election -- the labor unions, who are in favor of the job-creating pipeline, or the environmentalists, who fear another major oil spill and more pollution. Apparent from their pipeline rejection announcement and recent recess appointments, the administration finally decided to side with the environmentalists when&nbsp;another opportunity arose to acquiesce to the labor unions by appointing new members to the National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) &ndash; recess appointments that have been undergoing controversy. These appointments are currently under legal challenges because these appointments were made while there was no official recess declared by the Senate, making it a possible violation of the Constitution itself, according to the National Right to Work organization.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Now that the NLRB&rsquo;s vacancies are filled &ndash;- that is, unless/until the Supreme Court makes a ruling against it --, pro-union legislation can be passed to please the unions. From these actions, politics seem to be taking precedent over American jobs and energy independence that the administration vowed to prioritize at the beginning of their term, particularly by Obama\\''s promise in &ldquo;making sure jobs are available is the first thing I think about when I wake up every morning.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Possible political stratagems aside, the TransCanada Corp, the pipeline builder, is becoming restless -- they would prefer to do business with America, but would be just as willing to work with another country; in fact, Canada&rsquo;s Prime Minister is visiting China this month to discuss oil sales and other economic topics. If it comes to it, they will build their pipeline westward and export their petroleum to Asian markets, especially to China, an unfriendly Communist competitor to the United States growing in military and economic power every day. China\\''s energy expansion would deliver a huge economic and national security blow to America.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Proposed by Canada -- the most politically stable international ally to America -- several years ago, this 1,700-mile pipeline would pass through Montana, South Dakota, Nebraska, Kansas, and Oklahoma partly alongside another major pipeline to connect Canadian oil sands petroleum to Texas refineries. Because this pipeline crosses an international border, the approval of this project falls under the jurisdiction of the U.S. federal government.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Although a State Department statistic last year projected that the construction would generate around 6,000 jobs, TransCanada Corp estimates that the construction would create about 20,000 jobs, providing an enormous opportunity to stimulate the economy while promoting energy independence from the Middle East and Venezuela. This leaves the labor unions throughout the country as well as any American looking to improve the economy in favor of this project.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">On the flip side of the coin, the other preeminent Democrat constituency, the environmentalists, have been in fervor disapproval for years, despite the fact that America has been importing Canadian petroleum for years and a safe semi-transcontinental oil pipeline already exists in the country. Last August, a green-activist protest took place at the White House to pressure Obama into shooting down the pipeline deal. They claim that the extraction methods involved in retrieving oil sand petroleum produces more \\''green house\\'' gases than traditional oil, and according to Environment Canada, using oil sand petroleum instead of other oil accounts for 5% percent of Canadian car