etic car bomb in Tehran, marking him the fourth Iranian scientist death in two years. Other implements, such as computer viruses, have also been applied to curb Iran&rsquo;s nuclear development. The United States and Britain denied any involvement with the attacks, and Israeli spokesmen refused to comment on the subject, but it is most likely that it was Israel&rsquo;s intelligence organizations that have been carrying out these assassinations. The U.S.&rsquo;s CIA has similar apparatuses and security motives for such operations and therefore could have had&nbsp;a hand in some of the plots as well.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Iran has responded to these plots with their recent contentious decisions. In December last year, a U.S. drone &ndash; the RQ-170 Sentinel &ndash; malfunctioned and crashed into Iran. It was retrieved by Iranian officials and displayed on their television channels nearly intact. Rather than implement any operations to destroy the aircraft, the administration resorted to asking Iran to please return the drone &ndash; a request Iran&nbsp;sneered at. Worries amount that although Iran with its relatively primitive technology would not extract much from the drone, they could still sell it to Russia or China, either of which would be able to make better use of the potential intelligence and engineering secrets behind the drone. To push the envelope further, Iran demanded an apology from the United States for &lsquo;invading&rsquo; their airfield.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">About two weeks after this incident, a report came out about the finalization of America&rsquo;s sale of F-15SA fighting jets to Saudi Arabia, a nearby Middle Eastern country that serves for now as an ally to the United States. Saudi Arabia and Iran are currently local rivals, and stiffness between them rose higher after the attempted assassination of the Saudi ambassador to the United States on American soil earlier last year, which is believed to be plotted by Iranian officials. Although there were concerns that giving Saudi Arabia such weaponry would undermine Israel&rsquo;s military edge, it was still given the go-ahead on the account that Iran poses the greater danger to America&rsquo;s and Israel&rsquo;s national security.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">The implementation of the oil sanctions still continues today. In response to the embargo a month earlier, Iran threatened to&nbsp;target&nbsp;Western ships passing&nbsp;through the Strait of Hormuz, which is an important waterway for oil trade. The Iranian Parliament introduced a bill that would require foreign ships to be granted permission from Tehran to enter and leave the Strait. Several U.S. Navy ships moved closer to the waterway in retaliation&nbsp;to the threat, and declared that any blockage placed by Iran in this waterway would be deemed an act of war. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Despite all of this conflict, America still holds virtue above hate. Just days after Iran\\''s threatening of&nbsp;a Navy aircraft carrier against&nbsp;reentering the Strait of Hormuz, that same carrier rescued 13 Iranian sailors from pirates that held their ship hostage for over a month. The Iranian foreign ministry responded by upholding this as a \\"humanitarian and positive act.\\"</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Nevertheless, Iran still holds its world domination and terrorist ambitions, so the international&nbsp;tension with Iran remains far from dying down for a while yet.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\\"font-size: small;\\">Sources:</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong></strong><span style=\\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">U.S. Rescue of Iranian Sailors:&nbsp;<a href=\\"http://www.foxnews.com/world/2012/01/07/iran-hails-us-rescue-sailors-as-humanitarian-and-positive-act/\\" target=\\"_blank\\">http://www.foxnews.com/world/2012/01/07/iran-hails-us-rescue-sailors-as-humanitarian-and-positive-act/</a></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">Europeans Plan Oil Embargo On Iran: <a href=\\"http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970203471004577140583587139896.html?mod=WSJ_article_comments#articleTabs%3Darticle\\" target=\\"_blank\\">http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970203471004577140583587139896.html?mod=WSJ_article_comments#articleTabs%3Darticle</a></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">U.S. Finalizes Sale of F-15s to Saudi Arabia: <a href=\\"http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/12/29/us-to-sell-f-15s-to-saudi-arabia-officials-say/?intcmp=trending\\" target=\\"_blank\\">http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/12/29/us-to-sell-f-15s-to-saudi-arabia-officials-say/?intcmp=trending</a></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: tahoma,arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">Request for Return of Drone: <a href=\\"http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/12/13/us-formally-requests-drone-return-iran-scoffs/\\" target=\\"_blank\\">http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2011/12/13/us-formally-requests-drone-return-iran-scoffs/</a></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";s:7:"message";s:0:"";s:4:"user";s:3:"248";s:4:"time";i:1335227420;s:7:"changes";s:1:"0";}', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(114, 0, 126, 0, 'on', 2, '2', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:10:"End of War";s:7:"content";s:1840:"<p><span style=\\"font-family: arial black,avant garde; font-size: large;\\">End Of the War by Denise Castro</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: arial black,avant garde;\\"><img src=\\"http://htekidsnews.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/AP11121518514.jpg\\" alt=\\"\\" width=\\"492\\" height=\\"310\\" /></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Since March 20, 2003, the United States has been at war with Iraq. On Decemeber 15, 2011, the war officially came to a close. It came to a close quietly with a simple flag-lowering ceremony in Baghdad. This sharply contrasted with the initial 2003 bombardment of Baghdad almost nine years ago. President George W. Bush launched the war, believed Sadam Hussien to be hiding weapons of mass destruction.</p>\r\n<p>Despite President Bush&rsquo;s beliefs, no weapons of mass destruction were found. After the Hussein regime came tumbling down, the U.S. troops were seen not as heroes, but as intruders. The country of Iraq exploded into terrible violence.</p>\r\n<p>The war not only greatly disrupted Iraq, but also came to a high cost to America. All wars need funding, and in total, the U.S. spent more than $800 billion on the war in Iraq. 4,500 troops were killed and over 30,000 of them were injured. The U.S. says it is forever indebted to those men and women that served in this long and dangerous war.</p>\r\n<p>All of the troops were set to leave Iraq by the end of December 2011. What is to come in the New Year in regards to Iraq&rsquo;s state is yet to be determined. However, America is proud to welcome back its men and women and honor those who died bravely.</p>\r\n<p>Source:</p>\r\n<p><a href=\\"http://www.cnn.com/2011/12/15/world/meast/iraq-us-ceremony/index.html?hpt=wo_mid%23\\"><span style=\\"color: #0000ff;\\">http://www.cnn.com/2011/12/15/world/meast/iraq-us-ceremony/index.html?hpt=wo_mid#</span></a></p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";s:7:"message";