(115, 0, 126, 0, 'on', 2, '2', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:50:"SOPA and PIPA; what is their goal? by Madison Shaw";s:7:"content";s:3674:"<p align=\\"center\\">SOPA and PIPA; what is its goal?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There has been a lot of talk about the two bills, SOPA and PIPA. What do these two acronyms stand for? SOPA stands for &ldquo;Stop online piracy act&rdquo;. This bill is inside the House of Representatives.&nbsp; PIPA stands for &ldquo;Protect IP Act&rdquo;. PIPA originated from the Senate. &nbsp;I&rsquo;m sure that no one thinks that piracy should be legal, but what are these bills really meant to do?<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Let&rsquo;s start off with the basics. Media companies have always been looking for ways to stop piracy. They&rsquo;ve already tried ideas such as suing individual users; getting ISP&rsquo;s to take action against subscribers, and trying to make the government shut down domains that are based in the United States. There is one problem with that. None of these methods can stop overseas websites, such as The Pirate Bay and MegaUpload from stealing copyrights.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This is what supposedly prompted the birth of SOPA and PIPA.&nbsp; Both SOPA and PIPA are aimed at foreign websites that fringe on copyright material.&nbsp; This doesn&rsquo;t only have to do with movies and songs, but can also counterfeit consumer goods and medication. One way that they would do this, is by blocking domain names that infringe on copyrighted material.&nbsp; One example of this could be, Comcast preventing their customers from accessing overseas websites, however the IP address could still be accessible.&nbsp; The second method that they could use would order payment providers, advertisers, and search engines to stop doing business with an infringing website. So in other words, the right holders would request that funding be cut off from an infringing site.&nbsp; Links to that website would also be removed.&nbsp; So in other words, they&rsquo;re cutting of their money supply.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Many people however, breathe the sign of relief because many Americans have ban together to voice their opinion against these bills.&nbsp; Why are so many people opposed to these bills passing?&nbsp; SOPA and PIPA give the entertainment industry the power to censor sites that &ldquo;allegedly&rdquo; engage in copyright infringement.&nbsp; This means, they&rsquo;re guilty until proven innocent!&nbsp; The problem is, after their money supply is cut off they no longer have the financial means to prove their innocence in court. &nbsp;Search engines will censor results from searches.&nbsp; If you type an oversea website domain on a search engine, the domain could be taken out of the search engine&rsquo;s index.&nbsp; What they are doing, is limiting your index. Some people are afraid that it creates the building blocks for a great American firewall. Many people fear that these bills would threaten websites, such as Google, Youtube, and Facebook. Uploading videos to Youtube or Facebook could then be considered a crime. This would seem to be a fundamental attack on the foundations that make up the internet.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Most likely, this bill will pass in one form or another.&nbsp;&nbsp; It looks like Washington is listening to copyright holders and their powerful pals.&nbsp; For now, we must wait to see the outcome of these two powerful bills.</p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"1";s:7:"message";s:0:"";s:4:"user";s:3:"277";s:4:"time";i:1328658681;s:7:"changes";s:1:"1";}', '', '', '', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:50:"SOPA and PIPA; what is their goal?