(116, 0, 126, 0, 'on', 2, '2', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:25:"Can School Make You Sick?";s:7:"content";s:2777:"<p>&nbsp;<span style=\\"font-family: times new roman,times; font-size: large;\\">\\"Are Schools Making Children Sick?\\"</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: times new roman,times; font-size: large;\\">By: Gianna Torres</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: times new roman,times; font-size: medium;\\">I recently read an article on cnn.com. This article I read was entitled \\"Are schools making kids sick?\\" I automatically clicked on this because the titled striked my interest. As I was reading this article it brought up a very good point with supported facts. After I read the article I asked myself, \\"Could brick and mortar schools actually be making children sick?\\" I remember when I attended public school from kindergarten to the seventh grade I was always sick. Usually I would have the common cold. But ever since I\\''ve switched to virtual schooling I\\''ve only gotten sick once a year. Therefore this reduces my absences a lot and allows me to learn with clarity. I always believed that from being in close contact with other students it allowed for germs to spread more therefore becoming sick often. The CNN article I read though opened my mind to a different possibilty. Which was that some schools may not be up to par. For example in this article I read that a boy missed fifty three days of school because of persistenly becoming ill. He was coming down with respiratory infections, wet cough, and terrible headachs. However his persistent illness became pneumonia. This could easily be blamed on the H1N1 and not getting your flu shot. Not so fast. When it came time for summer vacation and the boy was out of school he was perfectly healthy. He would ride his bike and enjoy his time. But once he was back in school within teen weeks he came down with a respiratory infection. Once this happened it was brought to his mother\\''s attention that the school could be making him sick. Not only are students at risk for problems like this but teachers are too.&nbsp;&nbsp; Fresh air in a school is very important. It can lead to a better learning environment. There was a test done to the school that the boy attended to see if there were any mold problems. The results of this test were not surprising at all. The test found elevated levels of mold in the gymnasium, cafeteria, and two other rooms. These results made the school district shell out $16,000.00 for a cleaning. Now the school is considering temporaly closing to fix a leaky roof. The boy\\''s mother now homeschools him because she does not want any chances taken with his health again.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: times new roman,times; font-size: medium;\\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>Courtesy of*http://www.cnn.com/2012/01/14/health/school-indoor-air-pollution/index.html?hpt=he_c2</p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";s:7:"message";s:0:"";s:4:"user";s:3:"271";s:4:"time";i:1328724942;s:7:"changes";s:1:"1";}', '', '', '', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:25:"Can School Make You Sick?";s:7:"content";s:2777:"<p>&nbsp;<span style=\\"font-family: times new roman,times; font-size: large;\\">\\"Are Schools Making Children Sick?\\"</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: times new roman,times; font-size: large;\\">By: Gianna Torres</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: times new roman,times; font-size: medium;\\">I recently read an article on cnn.com. This article I read was entitled \\"Are schools making kids sick?\\" I automatically clicked on this because the titled striked my interest. As I was reading this article it brought up a very good point with supported facts. After I read the article I asked myself, \\"Could brick and mortar schools actually be making children sick?\\" I remember when I attended public school from kindergarten to the seventh grade I was always sick. Usually I would have the common cold. But ever since I\\''ve switched to virtual schooling I\\