1335227366;s:7:"changes";s:1:"0";}', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(120, 0, 126, 5, 'on', 2, '2', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:56:"Google developing car that drives itself by Madison Shaw";s:7:"content";s:4055:"<p align=\\"center\\">Google developing car that drives it self</p>\r\n<p>Tom Vanderbilt has recently hit the road to test a self-driving car, which can drive itself with more particularity and efficiency than any other human driver. Vanderbilt says that the car, which has been secretly developed by Google, brings a safe and fluent ride, even at highway speeds by using its laser rooftop sensor and a GPS tracking system.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\\"http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2010/10/10/us/10google-span/10google-span-articleLarge.jpg\\" alt=\\"\\" width=\\"460\\" height=\\"256\\" border=\\"0\\" />&nbsp;courtesy of: <a href=\\"http://www.nytimes.com/\\">www.nytimes.com</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The vehicle is causing car companies to consider their own models, such as BMW, Audi, and Mercedes. &nbsp;This car works by using artificial-intelligence software that senses cars nearby and mimics human reaction.&nbsp; This car also allows a human to drive it at any time, and override the system at any time. So, you can drive for a while and then you can take a break. Many people find this useful when on trips, or if you feel too tired to drive. Seven test cars have driven 1,000 miles without human assistance and more than 140,000 miles with occasional human assistance. &nbsp;Engineers said, the only accident was when the car was rear-ended at a stop light, which wasn&rsquo;t the fault of the Google automobile. One of the cars drove itself down one of steepest and curviest roads in the nation. This car was tested at the Google campus; the navigation system was installed on the Prius. The car was then tested in city traffic. The car followed the speed limits, which it remembered because every road is included in its database. This car can even cater to different driving personalities; such as cautious and aggressive. Scientist, Christopher Urmson went behind the wheel but wasn&rsquo;t controlling the vehicle. To access control of the car, you could hit a red button near your right hand, touch the brake or turn the steering wheel. He did this twice, when a bicyclist ran a red light, and when a car in front backed into a parking space. Urmson added that the car was gaining attention.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Google hired more than a dozen workers, all with a perfect driving record, to sit in the driver&rsquo;s seat, each getting paid about fifteen dollars an hour. &nbsp;Google is using six Priuses and an Audi TT for the project. The car&rsquo;s goal is an example of Google&rsquo;s eagerness to gamble on a vehicle that may not pay off. One way that Google could make a profit would be to give information and GPS services for creators of autonomous automobiles.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; These cars are years from mass production, but these cars have the potential to transform society as much as the internet has. These cars have a faster reaction time than humans and do not get sleepy like humans. &nbsp;These factors alone would help reduce auto accidents. If accidents are reduced, then these cars can be made lighter, thereby reducing gas consumption. In order for these cars to be truly safer, they must be more reliable than a personal computer, which we all know, tend to crash or become infected with viruses. The Google research program which uses artificial intelligence to transform the automobile is proof that Google&rsquo;s goals are much higher than just the search engine. The forty-three year old director of the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Sebastian Thrun, was the brainchild of this project.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This truly sounds like a car reminiscent of the movie &ldquo;Back to the Future&rdquo;. Some never thought that a car would be able to drive itself, but the future remains to be seen.</p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"1";s:7:"message";s:0:"";s:4:"user";s:3:"277";s:4:"time";i:1330025637;s:7:"changes";s:1:"1";}', 'a:4:{i:0;s:5:"Emily";i:1;s:4:"Kole";i:2;s:3:"277";i:3;s:4:"Liam";}', 'a:4:{i:0;i:1332851493;i:1;i:1333127773;i:2;i:1334260162;i:3;i:1334667299;}', 'a:4:{i:0;s:283:"<p><span style=\\"color: #ff0000;\\">That is so cool. I bet someday everyone will have one. Technology is always changing. I\\''m sure that by the time I can drive that there will be something even better. SO <span style=\\"text-decoration: line-through;\\">COOL</span> AWESOME!</span></p>";i:1;s:150:"<p style=\\"text-align: left;\\"><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><em><strong>Sweet! </strong></em></span>Maybe I can have one at twelvw.</p>";i:2;s:17:"<p>Thank you!</p>";i:3;s:58:"<p>maybe this will change the 16 year old driving law!</p>";}', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:56:"Google developing car that drives itself by Madison Shaw";s:7:"content";s:4055:"<p align=\\"center\\">Google developing car that drives it self</p>\r\n<p>Tom Vanderbilt has recently hit the road to test a self-driving car, which can drive itself with more particularity and efficiency than any other human driver. Vanderbilt says that the car, which has been secretly developed by Google, brings a safe and fluent ride, even at highway speeds by using its laser rooftop sensor and a GPS tracking system.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\\"http://graphics8.nytimes.com/images/2010/10/10/us/10google-span/10google-span-articleLarge.jpg\\" alt=\\"\\" width=\\"460\\" height=\\"256\\" border=\\"0\\" />&nbsp;courtesy of: <a href=\\"http://www.nytimes.com/\\">www.nytimes.com</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The vehicle is causing car companies to consider their