(121, 0, 126, 3, 'on', 2, '2', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:33:"The History of St. Patrick\\''s Day";s:7:"content";s:3429:"<p align=\\"center\\"><span style=\\"font-size: medium;\\"><strong><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri;\\">St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day</span></span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p align=\\"center\\"><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">By Corinne McCarthy</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day is the day when everyone is Irish! Ironically, the man it&rsquo;s named after wasn&rsquo;t even Irish. St. Patrick was born in Britain while it was still part of the Roman Empire, circa 387 A.D. When he was a teenager, he was kidnapped and brought to Ireland as a slave. He escaped from slavery and became a Catholic priest. He was later made a bishop. He returned to Ireland in 433 A.D. to teach the Catholic faith to the Irish. The day he died, March 17, is the day we celebrate St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day has been celebrated in Ireland since the ninth century, but the tradition of the St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day parade was started in the United States. The first parade was held on March 17, 1762, and the participants of the parade were Irish soldiers in the British military. Irish Aid societies were later established in the U.S. and held parades of their own, but in 1848, several societies in New York City decided to combine their parades into one. Today, cities across the U.S. have their own parades, but the New York parade is still the largest in the country. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The practice of dyeing the Chicago River green began in 1962. The dye was originally intended to find illegal sewage discharges. On St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day in 1962, it was used to festoon the river instead. Some claim, however, that Savannah, Georgia, first attempted to dye its river green, but the attempt failed. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In Ireland, St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day is a religious holiday and the celebrations start with Mass in the morning. St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day is during the season of Lent, and this season used to require Catholics to abstain from meat all through Lent instead of just on Fridays and Ash Wednesday. On this holiday, Catholics were allowed to eat meat and they celebrated with traditional Irish dishes, such as Irish bacon and cabbage. Before the 1970s, Irish pubs were closed on St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day, but now they remain open and Ireland uses this holiday to increase tourism.&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">Sources: </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">http://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=89</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">http://www.history.com/topics/st-patricks-day&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri;\\">&nbsp;</span></p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"1";s:7:"message";s:0:"";s:4:"user";s:3:"264";s:4:"time";i:1331927440;s:7:"changes";s:1:"1";}', '', '', '', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:33:"The History of St. Patrick\\''s Day";s:7:"content";s:3429:"<p align=\\"center\\"><span style=\\"font-size: medium;\\"><strong><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri;\\">St. Patrick&rsquo;s Day</span></span></str