(133, 0, 70, 3, 'on', 2, '2', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:13:"Cinco de Mayo";s:7:"content";s:2053:"<p align=\\"center\\"><span style=\\"font-size: medium;\\"><strong><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri;\\">Cinco de Mayo </span></span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p align=\\"center\\"><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">By Corinne McCarthy</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\\"font-size: small;\\"> Cinco de Mayo commemorates a Mexican victory over France in the Battle of Puebla. When Mexico defaulted on its debts to Britain, Spain, and France, the three countries attacked Mexico. While Spain and Britain eventually withdrew their army, France&rsquo;s Napoleon seized the chance to expand his empire to North America. In the town called Puebla Los Angeles (now named after the Mexican general Zaragoza), 2,000 Mexican troops defeated 6,000 French troops. Though not considered a significant win, it greatly buoyed the spirits of the Mexican military and gained popularity and support for the resistance movement against France.&nbsp; &nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cinco de Mayo, though widely celebrated in the U.S., isn&rsquo;t even considered a federal holiday in Mexico. Most celebrations take place in the Mexican state of Puebla. To commemorate this event, Mexicans reenact the battle and hold military parades. Most people treat it like an ordinary day, however, and no businesses are closed in honor of the day. In the United States, people hold parades and parties, play mariachi music, and dance Mexican folk dances. Traditional Mexican foods such as tacos and mole poblano are eaten. Cinco de Mayo in the U.S. has evolved from the commemoration of a military victory to a celebration of the Mexican culture. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">Source:&nbsp; http://www.history.com/topics/cinco-de-mayo</span></p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";s:7:"message";s:0:"";s:4:"user";s:3:"264";s:4:"time";i:1336153343;s:7:"changes";s:1:"1";}', '', '', '', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:13:"Cinco de Mayo";s:7:"content";s:2053:"<p align=\\"center\\"><span style=\\"font-size: medium;\\"><strong><span style=\\"text-decoration: underline;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri;\\">Cinco de Mayo </span></span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p align=\\"center\\"><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">By Corinne McCarthy</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\\"font-size: small;\\"> Cinco de Mayo commemorates a Mexican victory over France in the Battle of Puebla. When Mexico defaulted on its debts to Britain, Spain, and France, the three countries attacked Mexico. While Spain and Britain eventually withdrew their army, France&rsquo;s Napoleon seized the chance to expand his empire to North America. In the town called Puebla Los Angeles (now named after the Mexican general Zaragoza), 2,000 Mexican troops defeated 6,000 French troops. Though not considered a significant win, it greatly buoyed the spirits of the Mexican military and gained popularity and support for the resistance movement against France.&nbsp; &nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cinco de Mayo, though widely celebrated in the U.S., isn&rsquo;t even considered a federal holiday in Mexico. Most celebrations take place in the Mexican state of Puebla. To commemorate this event, Mexicans reenact the battle and hold military parades. Most people treat it like an ordinary day, however, and no businesses are closed in honor of the day. In the United States, people hold parades and parties, play mariachi music, and dance Mexican folk dances. Traditional Mexican foods such as tacos and mole poblano are eaten. Cinco de Mayo in the U.S. has evolved from the commemoration of a military victory to a celebration of the Mexican culture. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\\"font-family: Calibri; font-size: small;\\">Source:&nbsp; http://www.history.com/topics/cinco-de-mayo</span></p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";s:7:"message";s:0:"";s:4:"user";s:3:"248";s:4:"time";i:1337196699;s:7:"changes";s:1:"0";}', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(134, 7, 0, 0, '', 2, '1', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:27:"Welcome, to the Grade Code.";s:7:"content";s:2701:"<h1 style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: large;\\">Wha-? ACK! Where did you come from?</span></h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: large;\\">Erm, I wasn\\''t sleeping, no not at all! Hehe...</span></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">So, uh, you\\''re interested in the Grade Code, eh? Well I can tell you all about it, I\\''m in charge, I\\''m the master, I\\''m....</span></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">Dang. The Wanderer just told me to knock it off....</span></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><strong><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">Ahem. Sorry about that. Otaku can be...annoying, at times.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><strong><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">Are you interested in helping create a video game?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><strong><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">I need you to help design the Grade Code, so I can help train students in the art of (insert term here).</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><strong><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">We need coders, storyline writers, artists, and many other positions.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><strong><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">Our meetings are Fridays at 1:30, in the Grade Code MMORPG room.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><strong><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">Contact Matthew Farra for more information at (insert Matt\\''s email here).</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><strong><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">I\\''m counting you.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif;\\">And so am I!</span></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: medium;\\">Sigh....yes Otaku...why do you go....blow up a rock or something...</span></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: small;\\">Yay! Explosions!</span></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-family: comic sans ms,sans-serif; font-size: medium;\\">Sigh....</span></p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";s:7:"message";s:0:"";s:4:"user";s:3:"248";s:4:"time";i:1337198948;s:7:"changes";s:1:"1";}', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', ''),
(135, 8, 0, 0, 'on', 0, '1', 'a:7:{s:5:"title";s:26:"Pink Slime by Madison Shaw";s:7:"content";s:13371:"<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><strong>&nbsp; Pink Slime</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\\"text-align: center;\\"><span style=\\"font-size: xx-small;\\"><strong>By: Madison Shaw </strong></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;For a number of years prior to 2011, to assist with supply, McDonald&rsquo;s USA used some lean beef trimmings treated with ammonia in our burgers. We were among other food retailers who used this safe product.&rdquo; Issued McDonalds. Wait a second, &ldquo;Lean beef trimmings treated with ammonia&rdquo;. What exactly are these beef trimmings? Let us learn more about the beef trimmings that McDonalds, along with other food retailers, have secretly been using for years.</p>\r\n<p><img class=\\"rg_i\\" style=\\"margin: 0px auto; display: block;\\" src=\\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\\" alt=\\"\\" name=\\"J5XSiUp_Qyf9RM:\\" width=\\"182\\" height=\\"161\\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2002, Gerald Zirnstein, a food scientist, was involved in a project which identifies what was being included in our ground beef. Zirnstein referred to the beef trimmings along with its ammonia treatments as Pink Slime, in an e-mail to his colleague. Does that sound appetizing to you? Remember, this is coming from a food scientist and not an average American. If a food scientist refers to the beef trimmings as Pink Slime, then why does the USDA think otherwise? \\"The process used to produce LFTB is safe and has been used for a very long time, and adding LFTB to ground beef does not make that ground beef any less safe to consume&rdquo; states the USDA. Let us determine whether Pink Slime is as safe as the USDA claims it to be.</p>\r\n<p>Pink Slime is a beef based food additive that can be added to ground beef and beef based meats. It contains bits of ground beef, fat, connective tissue, and sinew. &nbsp;The fat is then separated from the trimmings in a centrifuge. In the 1990s, the Beef Products incorporation added ammonia gas into the ground beef supplement. This was to increase the PH and rid it of any bacteria. If this mystery meat doesn&rsquo;t sound pleasant, you&rsquo;re not alone. In 2008, The Washington Post even stated that Pink Slime made up 25% of beef products. In 2011 and 2012, the Pink Slime topic grew attention to the public and the media. Public attention grew rapidly in March 2012, when ABC News reported the percentage of Pink Slime in our beef products.</p>\r\n<p>The topic of beef trimmings in school lunches frightens many people. The USDA has ordered seven million pounds of Pink Slime from Beef Products incorporation, to be sent to schools across America. &ldquo;Even putting the &lsquo;yuck factor&rsquo; aside, there are some very valid reasons to question why anyone, let alone children, should eat this product&rdquo;, says Dr. Joseph Mercola. Carl Custer, a Microbiologist, states that these beef trimmings are toxic because they are accessed from cow parts that are contaminated with E. Coli and other toxic bacteria. Whereas, this is the reason why the trimmings need to be treated with ammonia gas. Carl Custer added, &ldquo;We originally called it soylent pink. We looked at the product and we objected to it because it used connective tissues instead of muscle. It was simply not nutritionally equivalent to ground beef. My main objection was that it was not meat.&rdquo; Custer also added that Pink Slime is not nutritionally competent for children. Then why are they still adding the mystery meat to the school lunches? &nbsp;The ammonia treatment is also toxic and can turn into ammonium nitrate, which is used in cleaning synthetics and fertilizer.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;The &ldquo;lean beef trimmings&rdquo; are not added to labels in grocery stores, so it is hard to tell whether or not you are eating Pink Slime. Pink slime has been used by fast food restaurants, including McDonald&rsquo;s, Taco Bell, and Burger King. However, once this issue was revealed to the public, they supposedly stopped adding it in their products. So, if Pink Slime is not good enough for McDonalds or Taco Bell, then why is it good enough for the USDA? Why is Pink Slime is still put in school lunches?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;If you do not want to eat Pink Slime, you have options. You can buy USDA labeled organic meat, which by law cannot contain Pink Slime. You could also support a trusted local farmer.&nbsp; Supporting a local farmer will enable you to know exactly where your food is coming from.&nbsp; Remember you have options but the choice is yours.&nbsp;</p>";s:8:"comments";s:1:"1";s:7:"message";s:0:"";s:4:"user";s:3:"277";s:4:"time";i:1337619917;s:7:"changes";s:1:"1";}', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '');
